7 And I turned to the sea of all wisdom;
8 I said: “What is this one saying? and what does
9 the other fire respond? and who are those who made it?”

25 My leader descended into the boat,
26 and then made me enter near him;
27 and only when I was inside did it seem laden.

34 And I to him: “If I come, I do not remain;
35 but who are you, who have made yourself so ugly?”
36 He responded: “See that I am one who weeps.”

37 And I to him: “With weeping and with sorrow,
38 cursed spirit, you remain;
39 because I know you, you are still all filthy.”

40 Then he extended to the boat both hands;
41 for which the skillful master pushed him away,
42 saying: “Go there with the other dogs!”

43 Then he encircled my neck with his arms;
44 he kissed my face and said: “Noble disdainful one,
45 blessed is she who was enclosed in you!

46 That was in the world a proud person;
47 goodness is not that adorns her memory:
48 thus is her shadow here furious.

61 All were crying: “To Filippo Argenti!”;
62 and the Florentine spirit bizarre
63 turned upon himself with teeth.

64 There we left him, and I narrate no more of it;
65 but in my ears struck a pain,
66 for which I lowered my eyes, intent, barred.

112 I could not hear what he offered to them;
113 but he did not stay there with them long,
114 because each one turned back to test [the way].

124 This their arrogance is not new;
125 because already they used it to a less secret door,
126 which without a lock is still found.
